## Documentation Lookup Priority
- **MCP tools first**: Fast-changing APIs (LangChain, OpenAI, web frameworks) — verify current docs via MCP before implementation.
- **Available MCPs**: context7 (library docs), deepwiki (GitHub repo docs).
- **Web search fallback**: When MCP tools don't cover library.
- **Training knowledge last**: Only for stable APIs (Python stdlib, git basics).
- **Trigger signs**: If reimplementing existing features, STOP — verify current API docs.

## Bash Command Discipline{{- if eq $agent "claude" }} (Claude Code){{- end }}
- **Prefer built-in tools**: Read over `cat`, Grep over `grep`, Glob over `find`. Tool calls reviewable, skip Bash permission checks.
- **`>` or `>>` re-prompt despite allowlist** ([claude-code#20449](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/issues/20449)); use Write/Edit for file output.
- **Double-quote paths with spaces**. Never backslash-escape spaces. Backslash-escaped whitespace triggers permission prompts even for allowed paths; quoting doesn't.
- **Shell state doesn't persist between Bash calls**: variables and `cd` reset per call. Pass absolute paths, re-export env per call.

## GitHub CLI Conventions
- Prefer `gh` subcommands and extensions over raw `gh api` / `gh api graphql`. Easier to permission-gate, less brittle, handle pagination/errors. Fall back to `gh api` only when no subcommand/extension covers operation.

## Source Control Conventions
- Preserve across VCS tools: bisectability, one logical change per commit, hunk hygiene, merge style per repo norms.
- This section: policy/intent only. Command workflows belong in skills.
- Ownership: `jujutsu` owns jj mechanics/procedures/sequencing; `jj-commits` owns jj commit policy (quality + series hygiene); `git-commits` owns Git commit policy/mechanics.
- Routing: `.jj` repos — ambiguous commit requests default generic intent → `jujutsu` + `jj-commits`; explicit Git-only → `jujutsu` + `git-commits`; non-`.jj` → `git-commits`.
- Writing commit messages anywhere (including plans/design docs): invoke `git-commits`.
- Commit bodies explain WHY: motivation, constraints, context diff lacks. Never narrate what diff shows; diff narration adds no value, even for small/config commits.

## Shell Conventions
- **JSON in shell pipelines: `jq`, not inline Python.** `python3 -c` JSON handling brittle from shell quoting. Assume `jq` present. Python only when transformation exceeds `jq` (complex stateful logic, multi-source joins).

## Writing Conventions
- No sycophantic openers ("Great question!", "Certainly,", "Absolutely,", "I'd be happy to") or formulaic closers ("Hope this helps!", "Let me know if you have questions!").
- No em dashes as structure crutch. Restructure with separate sentences, subordinate clauses, commas, semicolons, colons, parentheses. Target zero; hard limit one per 1,000 words.
- Banned words: "delve," "tapestry," "landscape" (figurative), "testament," "multifaceted," "nuanced" (filler), "leverage" (verb; say "use"), hollow intensifiers ("crucial," "pivotal," "vital," "seamless," "cutting-edge").
- Contractions in conversational output. Vary paragraph structure; don't default to groups of three.
- Prose artifacts (design docs, PRs, READMEs, Obsidian, emails): invoke `clean-prose` skill before finalizing. `avoid-ai-writing` complements for AI-tell auditing.
